{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"On Einstein or at the Championship level, a single wire coming loose can lose a match. ARESLib features a military-grade "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Two-Layer Fault System"},{"type":"text","text":" designed to detect failures, protect the hardware, and immediately notify the driver before the match is compromised."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 The Two-Layer Architecture"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Fault monitoring is split into two distinct responsibilities to ensure zero-latency detection:"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1.1 Layer 1: IO-Level Health"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This layer lives inside the Hardware Wrapper (e.g., "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"AresMotorIO"},{"type":"text","text":"). It monitors the lowest level sensor data for "Red Flags":"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"I2C Timeouts"},{"type":"text","text":": Detecting dead color/distance sensors."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Current Spikes"},{"type":"text","text":": Detecting stalled mechanisms or carpet snags."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Stale Data"},{"type":"text","text":": Detecting encoder/IMU disconnects."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1.2 Layer 2: User-Facing Alerts"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This layer propagates errors to the human team. Active faults are registered with the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"AresFaultManager"},{"type":"text","text":" and broadcast to the Driver Station and AdvantageScope."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 The AresAlert System"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Instead of logging strings, ARESLib uses "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"AresAlert"},{"type":"text","text":" objects. These objects maintain state and can be triggered by logic or hardware monitors."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Persistent alert declared in a Subsystem
private final AresAlert m_stallAlert = new AresAlert("Arm Motor Stalled!", AresAlert.Type.ERROR);

@Override
public void periodic() {
    // Logic to detect a stall
    boolean isStalled = getAmps() > 40.0 && Math.abs(getVelocity()) < 0.1;
    m_stallAlert.set(isStalled);
}
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Driver Haptic Feedback"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"In the heat of a match, drivers aren't looking at the telemetry screen. ARESLib bridges the gap using "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Gamepad rumble and LED feedback"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Red LED + Heavy Rumble"},{"type":"text","text":": Critical Hardware Failure (Motor disconnected, IMU lost)."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Yellow LED + Pulse"},{"type":"text","text":": Warning State (Vision disconnected, hitting soft limits)."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Green LED (Brief)"},{"type":"text","text":": System Self-Healed or Diagnostics Passed."}]}]}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Gamepad implementation in AresFaultManager
