{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Robots don't just run on code; they run on "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"electricity"},{"type":"text","text":". In the final 30 seconds of a match, your battery voltage drops, mechanisms slow down, and aggressive maneuvers can cause a "brownout" (reboot). ARESLib's Power Management system ensures your robot remains stable even at low voltage."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 Voltage Compensation"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"As the battery drops from 13.5V to 10.0V, your motor's "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"kV"},{"type":"text","text":" (velocity per volt) remains the same, but the available "ceiling" decreases. ARESLib automatically scales your feedforward and PID outputs based on the instantaneous battery voltage."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Inside DriveIOReal.java
double voltage = AresHardwareManager.getBatteryVoltage();
m_leftMotor.setPower(commandedVolts / voltage);
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Dynamic Load Shedding"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"If the battery drops below a safety threshold (e.g., 9.0V), ARESLib begins "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Load Shedding"},{"type":"text","text":". It calculates a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"masterPowerScale"},{"type":"text","text":" that smoothly throttles non-essential actuators to ensure the Control Hub doesn't reboot."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" The `AresHardwareManager` monitors both a **Voltage Sensor** and an optional **Floodgate Current Sensor** to compute the safest power multiplier."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Scaling logic in AresHardwareManager
if (batteryVoltage < 9.0) {
    // Linearly scale from 100% to 0% power between 9V and 7V
    voltageScale = (batteryVoltage - 7.0) / 2.0;
}
masterPowerScale = Math.min(voltageScale, currentScale);
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 EMA Smoothing"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Motor startups cause massive, multi-millisecond current spikes that can jitter your sensors. ARESLib uses an "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Exponential Moving Average (EMA)"},{"type":"text","text":" filter on its current and voltage monitoring to ensure it reacts to trends, not noise."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"04 Mechanism-Specific Limits"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You can use "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"calculateLoadSheddedLimit"},{"type":"text","text":" to define custom behavior for mechanisms like intakes or scoring arms during low-power states."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Example: Limiting Arm Current when battery is low
double currentLimit = AresHardwareManager.calculateLoadSheddedLimit(
    40.0, // Max Amps (Nominal)
    20.0, // Min Amps (Low Power)
    12.0, // Nominal Voltage
    9.0   // Critical Voltage
);
m_armMotor.setCurrentLimit(currentLimit);
"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" The REV Control Hub reboots at ~6.5V. If your load shedding isn't aggressive enough, a simultaneous swerve sprint + arm deployment will reset your robot mid-match. **Always test with a partially discharged battery!**"}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"SmartAssistAlign"},{"type":"text","text":" enables semi-autonomous scoring where the driver maintains forward control while the robot automatically handles lateral positioning and rotational alignment. This is the secret to consistent scoring during high-pressure matches!"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 What is Smart Assist Align?"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Traditional autonomous scoring requires the driver to stop and let the robot take over. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"SmartAssistAlign"},{"type":"text","text":" allows continuous movement:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Driver controls"},{"type":"text","text":": Forward/backward speed only"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Robot handles"},{"type":"text","text":": Lateral (Y) alignment + rotational alignment"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":": Smooth, continuous scoring while driving"}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Quick Start"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.1 Basic Usage"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// In your OpMode or RobotContainer
