{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"In high-level FTC and FRC competition, stopping to score is a bottleneck. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Shot-On-The-Move"},{"type":"text","text":" (SOTM) allows your robot to maintain full-speed swerve maneuvers while accurately launching game pieces into the transition or scoring hub. ARESLib provides a championship-grade exact quadratic solver for this purpose."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 The Physics of Motion"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"When a robot shoots while moving, the projectile inherits the robot's horizontal velocity vector. Without compensation, the game piece will drift in the direction of the robot's travel, missing the target."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" To hit the target, we must find a release vector *V*shot such that *V*shot + *V*robot points exactly where the game piece needs to be when it reaches the target's position. This requires solving for the **Time of Flight (TOF)**."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 The Quadratic Solver"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Unlike simple lookup tables, "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"EliteShooterMath.java"},{"type":"text","text":" solves the underlying physics equation. It solves for "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"t"},{"type":"text","text":" in the following magnitude constraint:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"||Ptarget - (Probot + Vrobot Γö¼Γòû t)|| = Vshot Γö¼Γòû t"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This expands into a quadratic equation "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"at"},{"type":"text","text":"2 + "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"bt"},{"type":"text","text":" + "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"c"},{"type":"text","text":" = 0, where we solve for the positive real root of "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"t"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Interactive SOTM Solver"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Visualizing Vector Interception & Drift Compensation"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 The Quadratic Solver"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Unlike simple lookup tables, "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"EliteShooterMath.java"},{"type":"text","text":" solves the underlying physics equation. It solves for "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"t"},{"type":"text","text":" in the following magnitude constraint:"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"||Ptarget - (Probot + Vrobot Γö¼Γòû t)|| = Vshot Γö¼Γòû t"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This expands into a quadratic equation "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"at"},{"type":"text","text":"2 + "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"bt"},{"type":"text","text":" + "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"c"},{"type":"text","text":" = 0, where we solve for the positive real root of "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"t"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Integration with Odometry"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For SOTM to work, the robot must know its exact velocity and position on the field. This is why ARESLib uses high-frequency "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"250Hz Odometry"},{"type":"text","text":". Any latency in velocity reporting will result in a miss."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Example implementation in a Subsystem
public void updateSOTM() {
    Pose2d currentPose = m_poseEstimator.getLatestPose();
    ChassisSpeeds speeds = m_driveSubsystem.getFieldRelativeSpeeds();

    EliteShooterMath.calculateShotOnTheMove(
        currentPose,
        speeds,
        TARGET_X, TARGET_Y, TARGET_Z,
        RELEASE_HEIGHT,
        NOMINAL_SPEED,
        9.81, // Gravity
        0.0,  // Lift
        m_setpoint // Result object
    );

    if (m_setpoint.isValid) {
        m_hood.setAngle(m_setpoint.hoodRadians);
        m_flywheel.setVelocity(m_setpoint.launchSpeedMetersPerSec);
    }
}
"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" The calculation assumes the piece is released *instantly*. In reality, there is "launch latency" (time for the motor to rev and for the belt to carry the ball). ARESLib compensates for this by using a historical pose buffer to look "forward" into the future."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Complex robot behaviors shouldn't be a mess of nested if-statements. A State Machine ensures your robot is only ever in one well-defined state (e.g., "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"INTAKING"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"SCORING"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"IDLE"},{"type":"text","text":"). This eliminates "ghost bugs" where the robot tries to intake while the arm is up."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 Why State Machines?"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"State Machines provide predictability. By defining explicit states and transitions, you guarantee that:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Code only runs when it's supposed to."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transitions are validated (e.g., you can't go from "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"STOWED"},{"type":"text","text":" to "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"SCORING"},{"type":"text","text":" without passing through "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"LIFTING"},{"type":"text","text":")."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Telemetry is deterministic."}]}]}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Core Implementation"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.1 Define Your States"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Create an "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"enum"},{"type":"text","text":" to represent every possible state of your subsystem."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"public enum IntakeState {
    IDLE,
    INTAKING,
    REVERSING,
    FULL
}

private StateMachine<IntakeState> stateMachine = new StateMachine<>(IntakeState.IDLE);
"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.2 Defining Transitions"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"onEnter"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"onExit"},{"type":"text","text":", and "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"onWhile"},{"type":"text","text":" methods to define behavior."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"stateMachine.onEnter(IntakeState.INTAKING, () -> {
    intakeMotor.setVoltage(12.0);
});

stateMachine.onWhile(IntakeState.INTAKING, () -> {
    if (sensor.isTriggered()) {
        stateMachine.setState(IntakeState.FULL);
    }
});
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Visualizing States"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ARESLib automatically exports state machine graphs to "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"AdvantageScope"},{"type":"text","text":". You can see real-time transitions in the "State Machine" tab of the simulator, allowing for deep debugging of sequential logic."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" Always include an `ERROR` or `FAULT` state in your state machine. If a hardware fault is detected via the [Fault Resilience](/tutorials/fault-resilience) system, your state machine should automatically transition to a safe state."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Swerve drive is the gold standard for high-performance robotics. Unlike tank drive, swerve allows for "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"holonomic motion"},{"type":"text","text":"╬ô├ç├╢the ability to translate in any direction while rotating simultaneously. This tutorial breaks down the vector addition required to control individual modules."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 Vector Summation"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each swerve module's state (velocity and angle) is the result of two distinct components:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Translation Component"},{"type":"text","text":": The desired linear movement of the chassis (identical for all modules)."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Rotation Component"},{"type":"text","text":": The tangential velocity required to rotate the chassis around its center. This vector is always perpendicular to the module's position relative to the center."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" The final state for each module is the vector sum of these two components. This is why modules "swirl" when you rotate in place and "tilt" when you strafe while turning."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1.1 Interactive Kinematics Solver"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Visualizing Translation + Rotation Vector Addition"}]},{"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Second-Order Kinematics (Discretization)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"At high speeds, simply commanding velocity causes the robot to "skew" or drift during rotations. This happens because the robot's heading changes "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"italic"}],"text":"during"},{"type":"text","text":" the loop cycle."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// AresKinematics.discretize() implementation
public static ChassisSpeeds discretize(ChassisSpeeds speeds, double dt) {
    double velocityMagnitude = Math.sqrt(speeds.vx * speeds.vx + speeds.vy * speeds.vy);
    if (velocityMagnitude < 1e-6 || Math.abs(speeds.omega) < 1e-6) {
        return speeds;
    }

    double angleDisplacement = speeds.omega * dt;
    double sin = Math.sin(angleDisplacement) / angleDisplacement;
    double cos = (1.0 - Math.cos(angleDisplacement)) / angleDisplacement;

    return new ChassisSpeeds(
        speeds.vx * sin - speeds.vy * cos,
        speeds.vx * cos + speeds.vy * sin,
        speeds.omega
    );
}
"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" Discretization treats the robot's movement as a circular arc rather than a straight line between frames. This eliminates the "skew" effect when strafing while turning full-tilt."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Cosine Compensation"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"When a swerve module is commanded to change its angle by 90 degrees, it has no traction until it reaches the target. ARESLib applies "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Cosine Compensation"},{"type":"text","text":" to scale module velocity by the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"cosine"},{"type":"text","text":" of the angle error, ensuring we don't spin wheels that aren't facing the right way yet."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"PID controllers are powerful, but they are reactive. To achieve truly championship-grade motion, you need "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Feedforward"},{"type":"text","text":"╬ô├ç├╢the ability to predict the voltage required to achieve a target velocity. ARESLib provides a specialized "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"SysId"},{"type":"text","text":" suite to calculate these constants automatically."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 Understanding kS, kV, and kA"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ARESLib uses the standard WPILib-style Feedforward model:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kS (Static)"},{"type":"text","text":": The voltage required to overcome static friction and just start the motor moving."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kV (Velocity)"},{"type":"text","text":": The voltage required to maintain a steady state velocity (proportional to speed)."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kA (Acceleration)"},{"type":"text","text":": The voltage required to change velocity (proportional to acceleration)."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" By calculating these values, your robot can hit its targets instantly without waiting for the PID loop to "catch up" to the error."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Continuous SysId Tuning"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"FTC batteries are notorious for "voltage sag," and mechanical friction changes as bearings wear down. ARESLib features a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Continuous Tuner"},{"type":"text","text":" that runs in the background during practice to refine these constants."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Example: Initializing a Continuous Tuner for a Flywheel
private final ContinuousSysIdTuner m_tuner = new ContinuousSysIdTuner(
    "ShooterFlywheel",
    (volts) -> m_io.setVoltage(volts),
    () -> m_io.getVelocityMetersPerSec()
);

@Override
public void periodic() {
    if (m_isTuning) {
        m_tuner.update(); // Records data points automatically
    }
}
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Running a SysId Routine"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For one-time characterization, use the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"SysIdRoutine"},{"type":"text","text":" command. This will execute the "Quasistatic" and "Dynamic" ramps required for the SysId analysis tool."}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Quasistatic"},{"type":"text","text":": The motor voltage slowly ramps up linearly. This isolates the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kV"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kS"},{"type":"text","text":" values."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Dynamic"},{"type":"text","text":": The motor is blasted with full voltage. This isolates the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"kA"},{"type":"text","text":" (inertia) value."}]}]}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// Command-based SysId implementation
public Command getSysIdCommand() {
    return new SysIdRoutine(
        new Config(),
        new Mechanism(
            (volts) -> m_drive.setVoltage(volts),
            null, // No logging needed, handled by @AutoLog
            this
        )
    ).quasistatic(Direction.kForward);
}
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"04 Exporting to Desktop"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Once raw data is collected, ARESLib can export it as a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"SysId JSON"},{"type":"text","text":" file. This file can be imported directly into the FRC/FTC SysId GUI tool to generate the optimal gains."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" Always run SysId routines with the robot on blocks before testing on the ground. A failed characterization can result in sudden, full-speed uncontrolled movement."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Visualizing robot state is critical for debugging. Instead of messy print statements or slow dashboard updates, ARESLib uses a high-performance, structured telemetry pipeline based on the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"AdvantageKit"},{"type":"text","text":" pattern."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 AdvantageKit Pattern"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ARESLib implements its own version of the FRC AdvantageKit "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"@AutoLog"},{"type":"text","text":" pattern. Instead of manual "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"telemetry.addData()"},{"type":"text","text":" calls, you define your inputs in a structured way."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1.1 Define Inputs"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Create a static inner class with the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"@AutoLog"},{"type":"text","text":" annotation. This tells the ARESLib processor to generate logging hooks for these specific fields."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"@AutoLog
public static class DriveIOInputs {
    public double leftPositionRad = 0.0;
    public double rightPositionRad = 0.0;
    public double gyroYawDeg = 0.0;
}
"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1.2 Automated Logging"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"AresAutoLogger"},{"type":"text","text":" automatically picks up any field in your "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Inputs"},{"type":"text","text":" objects and sends it to the configured backend:"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"USB Log"},{"type":"text","text":": High-speed binary logging to a flash drive."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Dashboard"},{"type":"text","text":": Real-time telemetry for the driver station."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Rlog Server"},{"type":"text","text":": Wireless telemetry for desktop visualization."}]}]}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 Visualizing in 3D"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Using "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"AdvantageScope"},{"type":"text","text":", you can drag your "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Odometry"},{"type":"text","text":" data directly into a 3D field view. ARESLib provides built-in 3D model support for standard FTC game pieces and common robot chassis."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Log Replay"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Because input is decoupled from logic in ARESLib, you can feed a log file back into the robot code (even on your laptop) to reproduce bugs that happened during a real match. This is the ultimate "time travel" debugging tool."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" ARESLib's telemetry pipeline is designed to be **Zero-Allocation**. It pre-allocates buffers at startup to ensure that logging doesn't trigger Garbage Collection (GC) pauses during a match."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Odometry is fast but drifts over time. Vision is global but slow and noisy. "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Vision Fusion"},{"type":"text","text":" is the process of combining both to achieve a "source of truth" pose that is both high-frequency and drift-free. ARESLib uses a latency-compensating rollback algorithm to ensure bit-perfect accuracy."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 The Fusion Pipeline"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Fusion happens in three distinct layers to ensure reliability under competition stress:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"mermaid"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"graph TD
    A[Hardware Sensors<br/><i>Encoders + IMU</i>] -->|250Hz| B(Odometry Thread)
    C[AprilTag Cameras<br/><i>PhotonVision / Limelight</i>] -->|20Hz| D(Vision Subsystem)
    B --> E{AresPoseEstimator}
    D -->|Pose + Timestamp| E
    E --> F[Final Field Pose<br/><i>AdvantageScope 3D</i>]

    style A fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#CD7F32,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff
    style B fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#CD7F32,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff
    style C fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#B32416,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff
    style D fill:#1a1a1a,stroke:#B32416,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff
    style E fill:#CD7F32,stroke:#fff,stroke-width:2px,color:#000
    style F fill:#0d0d0d,stroke:#fff,stroke-width:2px,color:#fff
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 MegaTag 2.0 & Pose Seeding"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Traditional vision pose estimation (PnP) creates large "jumps" when tags are at awkward angles. ARESLib supports "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"MegaTag 2.0"},{"type":"text","text":", which uses the robot's IMU heading to seed the vision solve."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" By using the IMU to define the "Down" vector, the vision system only needs to solve for 2D translation and 1D rotation. This significantly reduces "pose ambiguity" and prevents the robot from teleporting into the floor or ceiling in the 3D visualizer."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Lag Compensation (Rollback)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Vision measurements are always "old" (e.g., 50ms ago) by the time the code receives them. The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"VisionFusionHelper"},{"type":"text","text":" handles this by:"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"3.1 Maintaining Buffers"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Maintaining a timestamped buffer of all previous odometry poses."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"3.2 Replaying Movement"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"When a vision sample arrives, "rolling back" to that exact timestamp, computing correction, and "replaying" all movement forward."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// VisionFusionHelper.java snippet
public static Pose2d applyVisionMeasurement(...) {
    Pose2d sample = poseBuffer.getSample(timestampSeconds);
    if (sample == null) return currentEstimate;

    // Compute correction AT the measurement timestamp
    double kX = 1.0 / (1.0 + visionStdDevs[0]);
    double kY = 1.0 / (1.0 + visionStdDevs[1]);

    Pose2d correctedRetroPose = new Pose2d(
        sample.getX() + xError * kX,
        sample.getY() + yError * kY,
        ...
    );

    // Replay movement forward to 'Now'
    Twist2d replayTwist = sample.log(currentEstimate);
    return correctedRetroPose.exp(replayTwist);
}
"}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"04 Tuning Trust (StdDevs)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You can tell the estimator how much to "trust" a vision measurement by adjusting the Standard Deviations. Large values = less trust; small values = strong correction."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" ARESLib automatically scales trust based on distance. If a tag is 5 meters away, we increase the StdDev (trust it less). If the robot is moving at 4 m/s, we increase it further to prevent motion blur artifacts from corrupting the pose."}]}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Deterministic performance requires avoiding the heap. In FTC, the Java Garbage Collector (GC) can trigger at any time. If it triggers during a tight control loop, your 20ms loop might balloon to 50ms or more, causing "jitter" in your odometry and PID controllers."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" No objects may be instantiated (using `new`) inside any method called by `OpMode.loop()` or `Command.execute()`."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"01 Why achieve zero-allocation?"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"When you create a new object, the JVM allocates memory on the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Heap"},{"type":"text","text":". When that object is no longer used, the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Garbage Collector"},{"type":"text","text":" must reclaim that memory. This process is non-deterministic and can pause your program's execution (a "GC Hang"). For a robot moving at 4 m/s, a 50ms pause means moving 20cm without any control input."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"02 How to achieve zero-allocation?"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.1 Use Pre-allocated Static Constants"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Instead of creating new "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Pose2d"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Rotation2d"},{"type":"text","text":" objects every tick, use static constants or pre-allocated buffers."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// BAD: Creates a new object every 20ms
Rotation2d angle = new Rotation2d(Math.toRadians(90));

// GOOD: Reusable constant
private static final Rotation2d NINETY_DEGREES = Rotation2d.fromDegrees(90);
"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.2 Object Pooling & Static Buffers"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For mathematical operations, use "Copy" or "Set" methods instead of creating new results. Most geometry classes in ARESLib provide a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"set()"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"interpolation()"},{"type":"text","text":" method that modifies an existing instance."}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"java"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"// BAD: Creates a new Pose2d object
Pose2d current = odometry.getPose();
Pose2d next = current.plus(transform); 

// GOOD: Update a pre-allocated buffer
private final Pose2d poseBuffer = new Pose2d();

public void periodic() {
    Pose2d current = odometry.getPose();
    // Update the buffer instead of creating new ones
    poseBuffer.set(current.getX(), current.getY(), current.getRotation());
}
"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2.3 Avoid List Allocations"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Don't use "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Stream"},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"ArrayList.addAll()"},{"type":"text","text":", or any lambda that captures variables inside the hot path. These frequently trigger hidden allocations."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"03 Verification"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"To verify your code is zero-allocation, use the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Android Studio Profiler"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"orderedList","attrs":{"start":1,"type":null},"content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Connect to your robot via ADB."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Open the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Profiler"},{"type":"text","text":" tab in Android Studio."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Click on the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Memory"},{"type":"text","text":" timeline."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Look for "Allocation Count." It should remain flat at "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"0"},{"type":"text","text":" during your OpMode's execution."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":" Allocating objects during `init()` or `robotInit()` is perfectly fine (and required). The Zero-Allocation rule only applies to the "Hot Path" (code that runs repeatedly during the match)."}]}]}

